revision.text:
==English==
===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|yesterday}}, {{m|enm|yisterday}}, {{m|enm|ȝesterdai}}, {{m|enm|ȝisterdai}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġiestrandæġ}}, {{m|ang|ġister dæġ}}, {{m|ang|ġestor dæġ}}, {{m|ang|ġeostran dæġ}}, equivalent to {{af|en|yester-|day}}; see there for more. Compare {{cog|sco|yisterday}}, {{m|sco|yesterday|t=yesterday}}, {{cog|got|𐌲𐌹𐍃𐍄𐍂𐌰𐌳𐌰𐌲𐌹𐍃|t=tomorrow|pos=adverb}}. Compare further {{cog|nl|gisteren}}, {{cog|de|gestern}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈjɛstədeɪ/|/ˈjɛstədɪ/}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|en|/ˈjɛstɚdeɪ/|/ˈjɛstɚdi/}}
* {{a|dated|Southern US folk speech}} {{IPA|en|/ˈjɪstɚdeɪ/|/ˈjɪstɚdi/}}<ref>{{R:PEAS|134|135}}</ref>
* {{audio|en|en-us-yesterday.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-yesterday.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# The [[day]] immediately before [[today]]; one day ago.
#: {{ux|en|Today is the child of '''yesterday''' and the parent of tomorrow.}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Yesterday''' was rainy, but by this morning it had begun to snow.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1899|author={{w|Hughes Mearns}}
|title={{w|Antigonish (poem)|Antigonish}}
|passage='''Yesterday''', upon the stair&nbsp;/ I met a man who wasn’t there&nbsp;/ He wasn’t there again today&nbsp;/ I wish, I wish he’d go away&nbsp;&hellip;}}
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} The [[past]], often in terms of being [[outdated]].
#: {{ux|en|'''yesterday's''' technology}}
#: {{ux|en|The worker of today is different from that of '''yesterday'''.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Macbeth|5|5|text=All our '''yesterdays''' have lighted fools the way to dusty death.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-22|volume=407|issue=8841|page=76|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21579801-making-sense-statistics-riddle-our-days-snakes-and-ladders Snakes and ladders]
|passage=Risk is everywhere. From tabloid headlines insisting that coffee causes cancer ('''yesterday''', of course, it cured it) to stern government warnings about alcohol and driving, the world is teeming with goblins. For each one there is a frighteningly precise measurement of just how likely it is to jump from the shadows and get you.}}
====Usage notes====
* The plural {{m|en|yesterdays}} is unusual and often poetic for the recent past, e.g. “all our yesterdays have come back to haunt us”.
* While pronunciations with {{IPAchar|/ˈjɪ-/}} are now dialectal, they were formerly found in the standard language. For example, writer and [[orthoepist]] {{w|Thomas Sheridan}} prescribed such a pronunciation in his work.<ref>{{cite-book|author=Thomas Sheridan|title=A Complete Dictionary of the English Language, Both with Regard to Sound and Meaning|volume=2|url= https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=pJoRAAAAIAAJ|archiveurl=|archivedate=|year=1790|publisher=C. Dilly}}</ref>
